# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: akka-http-scala
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The **actor model** in computer science is a mathematical model of concurrent computation that treats an *actor* as the basic building block of concurrent computation.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] In response to a message it receives, an actor can: make local decisions, create more actors, send more messages, and determine how to respond to the next message received.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Actors may modify their own private state, but can only affect each other indirectly through messaging (removing the need for lock-based synchronization).
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] It has been used both as a framework for a theoretical understanding of computation and as the theoretical basis for several practical implementations of concurrent systems.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The relationship of the model to other work is discussed in actor model and process calculi.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] According to Carl Hewitt, unlike previous models of computation, the actor model was inspired by physics, including general relativity and quantum mechanics.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] It was also influenced by the programming languages Lisp, Simula, early versions of Smalltalk, capability-based systems, and packet switching.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Following Hewitt, Bishop, and Steiger's 1973 publication, Irene Greif developed an operational semantics for the actor model as part of her doctoral research.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Two years later, Henry Baker and Hewitt published a set of axiomatic laws for actor systems.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Other major milestones include William Clinger's 1981 dissertation introducing a denotational semantics based on power domains and Gul Agha's 1985 dissertation which further developed a transition-based semantic model complementary to Clinger's.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] This resulted in the full development of actor model theory.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Research groups led by Chuck Seitz at California Institute of Technology (Caltech) and Bill Dally at MIT constructed computer architectures that further developed the message passing in the model.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The actor model adopts the philosophy that *everything is an actor*.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] This is similar to the *everything is an object* philosophy used by some object-oriented programming languages.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] There is no assumed sequence to the above actions and they could be carried out in parallel.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Decoupling the sender from communications sent was a fundamental advance of the actor model enabling asynchronous communication and control structures as patterns of passing messages.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Recipients of messages are identified by address, sometimes called "mailing address".
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Thus an actor can only communicate with actors whose addresses it has.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] It can obtain those from a message it receives, or if the address is for an actor it has itself created.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The actor model is characterized by inherent concurrency of computation within and among actors, dynamic creation of actors, inclusion of actor addresses in messages, and interaction only through direct asynchronous message passing with no restriction on message arrival order.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Over the years, several different formal systems have been developed which permit reasoning about systems in the actor model.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The actor model can be used as a framework for modeling, understanding, and reasoning about a wide range of concurrent systems.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The actor model is about the semantics of message passing.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Arguably, the first concurrent programs were interrupt handlers.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] During the course of its normal operation a computer needed to be able to receive information from outside (characters from a keyboard, packets from a network, *etc*).
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] So when the information arrived the execution of the computer was *interrupted* and special code (called an interrupt handler) was called to put the information in a data buffer where it could be subsequently retrieved.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] In the early 1960s, interrupts began to be used to simulate the concurrent execution of several programs on one processor.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Having concurrency with shared memory gave rise to the problem of concurrency control.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Originally, this problem was conceived as being one of mutual exclusion on a single computer.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra developed semaphores and later, between 1971 and 1973, Tony Hoare and Per Brinch Hansen developed monitors to solve the mutual exclusion problem.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] However, neither of these solutions provided a programming language construct that encapsulated access to shared resources.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] This encapsulation was later accomplished by the serializer construct ([Hewitt and Atkinson 1977, 1979] and [Atkinson 1980]).
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Each computational step was from one global state of the computation to the next global state.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The global state approach was continued in automata theory for finite-state machines and push down stack machines, including their nondeterministic versions.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Such nondeterministic automata have the property of bounded nondeterminism; that is, if a machine always halts when started in its initial state, then there is a bound on the number of states in which it halts.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra further developed the nondeterministic global state approach.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Hewitt argued that the actor model should provide the guarantee of service.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] In Dijkstra's model, although there could be an unbounded amount of time between the execution of sequential instructions on a computer, a (parallel) program that started out in a well defined state could terminate in only a bounded number of states [Dijkstra 1976].
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Consequently, his model could not provide the guarantee of service.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Dijkstra argued that it was impossible to implement unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Hewitt argued otherwise: there is no bound that can be placed on how long it takes a computational circuit called an *arbiter* to settle (see metastability (electronics)).
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The actor model features unbounded nondeterminism which was captured in a mathematical model by Will Clinger using domain theory.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] In the actor model, there is no global state.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Messages in the actor model are not necessarily buffered.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] This was a sharp break with previous approaches to models of concurrent computation.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The lack of buffering caused a great deal of misunderstanding at the time of the development of the actor model and is still a controversial issue.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Some researchers argued that the messages are buffered in the "ether" or the "environment".
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Also, messages in the actor model are simply sent (like packets in IP); there is no requirement for a synchronous handshake with the recipient.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] A natural development of the actor model was to allow addresses in messages.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Influenced by packet switched networks [1961 and 1964], Hewitt proposed the development of a new model of concurrent computation in which communications would not have any required fields at all: they could be empty.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Of course, if the sender of a communication desired a recipient to have access to addresses which the recipient did not already have, the address would have to be sent in the communication.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The original actor could accomplish this by sending a communication that includes the message it wishes to send, along with the address of the third actor that will handle the response.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] This third actor that will handle the response is called the *resumption* (sometimes also called a continuation or stack frame).
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] When the recipient actor is ready to send a response, it sends the response message to the *resumption* actor address that was included in the original communication.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] As opposed to the previous approach based on composing sequential processes, the actor model was developed as an inherently concurrent model.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] In the actor model sequentiality was a special case that derived from concurrent computation as explained in actor model theory.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Hewitt argued against adding the requirement that messages must arrive in the order in which they are sent to the actor.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] If output message ordering is desired, then it can be modeled by a queue actor that provides this functionality.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Such a queue actor would queue the messages that arrived so that they could be retrieved in FIFO order.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] So if an actor `X` sent a message `M1` to an actor `Y`, and later `X` sent another message `M2` to `Y`, there is no requirement that `M1` arrives at `Y` before `M2`.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] In this respect the actor model mirrors packet switching systems which do not guarantee that packets must be received in the order sent.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Not providing the order of delivery guarantee allows packet switching to buffer packets, use multiple paths to send packets, resend damaged packets, and to provide other optimizations.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] For more example, actors are allowed to pipeline the processing of messages.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] What this means is that in the course of processing a message `M1`, an actor can designate the behavior to be used to process the next message, and then in fact begin processing another message `M2` before it has finished processing `M1`.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Just because an actor is allowed to pipeline the processing of messages does not mean that it *must* pipeline the processing.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Whether a message is pipelined is an engineering tradeoff.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] How would an external observer know whether the processing of a message by an actor has been pipelined?
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] There is no ambiguity in the definition of an actor created by the possibility of pipelining.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Of course, it is possible to perform the pipeline optimization incorrectly in some implementations, in which case unexpected behavior may occur.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Another important characteristic of the actor model is locality.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Locality means that in processing a message, an actor can send messages only to addresses that it receives in the message, addresses that it already had before it received the message, and addresses for actors that it creates while processing the message.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Also locality means that there is no simultaneous change in multiple locations.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] In this way it differs from some other models of concurrency, *e.g.*, the Petri net model in which tokens are simultaneously removed from multiple locations and placed in other locations.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The idea of composing actor systems into larger ones is an important aspect of modularity that was developed in Gul Agha's doctoral dissertation, developed later by Gul Agha, Ian Mason, Scott Smith, and Carolyn Talcott.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] A key innovation was the introduction of *behavior* specified as a mathematical function to express what an actor does when it processes a message, including specifying a new behavior to process the next message that arrives.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Behaviors provided a mechanism to mathematically model the sharing in concurrency.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Behaviors also freed the actor model from implementation details, *e.g.*, the Smalltalk-72 token stream interpreter.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] However, the efficient implementation of systems described by the actor model require *extensive* optimization.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] See Actor model implementation for details.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Other concurrency systems (*e.g.*, process calculi) can be modeled in the actor model using a two-phase commit protocol.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] There is a *Computational Representation Theorem* in the actor model for systems which are closed in the sense that they do not receive communications from outside.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] In this way, ${\mathtt {S}}$ can be mathematically characterized in terms of all its possible behaviors (including those involving unbounded nondeterminism).
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] A consequence of the above theorem is that a finite actor can nondeterministically respond with an uncountable number of different outputs.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] One of the key motivations for the development of the actor model was to understand and deal with the control structure issues that arose in development of the Planner programming language.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Once the actor model was initially defined, an important challenge was to understand the power of the model relative to Robert Kowalski's thesis that "computation can be subsumed by deduction".
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Hewitt argued that Kowalski's thesis turned out to be false for the concurrent computation in the actor model (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Nevertheless, attempts were made to extend logic programming to concurrent computation.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] However, Hewitt and Agha [1991] claimed that the resulting systems were not deductive in the following sense: computational steps of the concurrent logic programming systems do not follow deductively from previous steps (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Recently, logic programming has been integrated into the actor model in a way that maintains logical semantics.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Migration in the actor model is the ability of actors to change locations.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] *E.g.*, in his dissertation, Aki Yonezawa modeled a post office that customer actors could enter, change locations within while operating, and exit.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] An actor that can migrate can be modeled by having a location actor that changes when the actor migrates.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] However the faithfulness of this modeling is controversial and the subject of research.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] A delicate point in the actor model is the ability to synthesize the address of an actor.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] In some cases security can be used to prevent the synthesis of addresses (see Security).
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] However, if an actor address is simply a bit string then clearly it can be synthesized although it may be difficult or even infeasible to guess the address of an actor if the bit strings are long enough.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] SOAP uses a URL for the address of an endpoint where an actor can be reached.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Since a URL is a character string, it can clearly be synthesized although encryption can make it virtually impossible to guess.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Synthesizing the addresses of actors is usually modeled using mapping.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The idea is to use an actor system to perform the mapping to the actual actor addresses.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] For example, on a computer the memory structure of the computer can be modeled as an actor system that does the mapping.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] In the case of SOAP addresses, it's modeling the DNS and the rest of the URL mapping.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Robin Milner's initial published work on concurrency was also notable in that it was not based on composing sequential processes.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] His work differed from the actor model because it was based on a fixed number of processes of fixed topology communicating numbers and strings using synchronous communication.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Later versions of CSP abandoned communication based on process names in favor of anonymous communication via channels, an approach also used in Milner's work on the calculus of communicating systems (CCS) and the π-calculus.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] These early models by Milner and Hoare both had the property of bounded nondeterminism.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Modern, theoretical CSP ([Hoare 1985] and [Roscoe 2005]) explicitly provides unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The actor model has been influential on both theory development and practical software development.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The actor model has influenced the development of the π-calculus and subsequent process calculi.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The actor model has had extensive influence on commercial practice.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] For example, Twitter has used actors for scalability.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Also, Microsoft has used the actor model in the development of its Asynchronous Agents Library.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] There are multiple other actor libraries listed in the actor libraries and frameworks section below.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Many of the ideas introduced in the actor model are now also finding application in multi-agent systems for these same reasons [Hewitt 2006b 2007b].
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] The key difference is that agent systems (in most definitions) impose extra constraints upon the actors, typically requiring that they make use of commitments and goals.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] A number of different programming languages employ the actor model or some variation of it.
[src:akka-http-scala/actor-model] Actor libraries or frameworks have also been implemented to permit actor-style programming in languages that don't have actors built-in.
[src:akka-http-scala/akka-toolkit] Language bindings exist for both Java and Scala.
[src:akka-http-scala/akka-toolkit] An actor implementation, written by Philipp Haller, was released in July 2006 as part of Scala 2.1.7.
[src:akka-http-scala/akka-toolkit] By 2008 Scala was attracting attention for use in complex server applications, but concurrency was still typically achieved by creating threads that shared memory and synchronized when necessary using locks.
[src:akka-http-scala/akka-toolkit] Aware of the difficulties with that approach and inspired by the Erlang programming language's library support for writing highly concurrent, distributed, and event-driven applications, the Swedish programmer Jonas Bonér created Akka to bring similar capabilities to the JVM.
[src:akka-http-scala/akka-toolkit] Bonér began working on Akka in early 2009 and wrote up his vision for it in June of that year.
[src:akka-http-scala/akka-toolkit] The first public release was Akka 0.5, announced in January 2010.
[src:akka-http-scala/akka-toolkit] Akka is now part of the Lightbend Platform together with the Play framework and the Scala programming language.
[src:akka-http-scala/akka-toolkit] In September 2022, Lightbend announced that Akka would change its license from the free software license Apache License 2.0 to a proprietary source-available license, known as the Business Source License (BSL).
[src:akka-http-scala/akka-toolkit] Any new code under the BSL would become available under the Apache License after three years.
[src:akka-http-scala/akka-toolkit] Apache Pekko is an Apache licensed fork of Akka.
[src:akka-http-scala/akka-toolkit] There are more than 250 public projects registered on GitHub which use Akka.
[src:akka-http-scala/akka-toolkit] Besides many web articles that describe the commercial use of Akka, there are also overview articles about it.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] The Akka HTTP modules implement a full server- and client-side HTTP stack on top of *akka-actor* and *akka-stream*.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] It’s not a web-framework but rather a more general toolkit for providing and consuming HTTP-based services.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] While interaction with a browser is of course also in scope it is not the primary focus of Akka HTTP.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Akka HTTP follows a rather open design and many times offers several different API levels for “doing the same thing”.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] You get to pick the API level of abstraction that is most suitable for your application.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] This means that, if you have trouble achieving something using a high-level API, there’s a good chance that you can get it done with a low-level API, which offers more flexibility but might require you to write more application code.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Akka HTTP has been driven with a clear focus on providing tools for building integration layers rather than application cores.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] As such it regards itself as a suite of libraries rather than a framework.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] A framework, as we’d like to think of the term, gives you a “frame”, in which you build your application.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] It comes with a lot of decisions already pre-made and provides a foundation including support structures that lets you get started and deliver results quickly.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] In a way a framework is like a skeleton onto which you put the “flesh” of your application in order to have it come alive.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] As such frameworks work best if you choose them before you start application development and try to stick to the framework’s “way of doing things” as you go along.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] For example, if you are building a browser-facing web application it makes sense to choose a web framework and build your application on top of it because the “core” of the application is the interaction of a browser with your code on the web-server.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] The framework makers have chosen one “proven” way of designing such applications and let you “fill in the blanks” of a more or less flexible “application-template”.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Being able to rely on best-practice architecture like this can be a great asset for getting things done quickly.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] However, if your application is not primarily a web application because its core is not browser-interaction but some specialized maybe complex business service and you are merely trying to connect it to the world via a REST/HTTP interface a web-framework might not be what you need.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] In this case the application architecture should be dictated by what makes sense for the core not the interface layer.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Also, you probably won’t benefit from the possibly existing browser-specific framework components like view templating, asset management, JavaScript- and CSS generation/manipulation/minification, localization support, AJAX support, etc.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Akka HTTP was designed specifically as “not-a-framework”, not because we don’t like frameworks, but for use cases where a framework is not the right choice.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Akka HTTP is made for building integration layers based on HTTP and as such tries to “stay on the sidelines”.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Therefore you normally don’t build your application “on top of” Akka HTTP, but you build your application on top of whatever makes sense and use Akka HTTP merely for the HTTP integration needs.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] On the other hand, if you prefer to build your applications with the guidance of a framework, you should give Play Framework a try, which both use Akka internally.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] If you come from Play and want to try Akka HTTP, we collected a side-by-side comparison to show how some Play routing features map to the Akka HTTP routing DSL.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Akka HTTP is provided as independent modules from Akka itself under its own release cycle.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Akka HTTP is compatible with Akka >= 2.10.11 and future Akka 2.x versions that are released during the lifetime of Akka HTTP 10.4.x.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] The modules, however, do *not* depend on `akka-actor` or `akka-stream`, so the user is required to choose an Akka version to run against and add a manual dependency to `akka-stream` of the chosen version.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] The Akka dependencies are available from Akka’s secure library repository.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] To access them you need to use a secure, tokenized URL as specified at https://account.akka.io/token.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Additionally, add the dependencies as below.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] The high-level, routing API of Akka HTTP provides a DSL to describe HTTP “routes” and how they should be handled.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Each route is composed of one or more level of `Directives``Directives` that narrows down to handling one specific type of request.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] For example one route might start with matching the `path` of the request, only matching if it is “/hello”, then narrowing it down to only handle HTTP `get` requests and then `complete` those with a string literal, which will be sent back as an HTTP OK with the string as response body.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] When you run this server, you can either open the page in a browser, at the following url: http://localhost:8080/hello, or call it in your terminal, via `curl http://localhost:8080/hello`.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Transforming request and response bodies between over-the-wire formats and objects to be used in your application is done separately from the route declarations, in marshallers, which are pulled in implicitly using the “magnet” pattern.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] This means that you can `complete` a request with any kind of object as long as there is an implicit marshaller available in scope.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Default marshallers are provided for simple objects like String or ByteString, and you can define your own for example for JSON.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] A common use case is to reply to a request using a model object having the marshaller transform it into JSON.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] In this case shown by two separate routes.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] The first route queries an asynchronous database and marshals the `Future[Option[Item]]``CompletionStage<Optional<Item>>` result into a JSON response.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] The second unmarshals an `Order` from the incoming request, saves it to the database and replies with an OK when done.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] The logic for the marshalling and unmarshalling JSON in this example is provided by the “spray-json”“Jackson” library.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] See JSON Support)JSON Support) for more information about integration with this library.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] One of the strengths of Akka HTTP is that streaming data is at its heart meaning that both request and response bodies can be streamed through the server achieving constant memory usage even for very large requests or responses.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Streaming responses will be backpressured by the remote client so that the server will not push data faster than the client can handle, streaming requests means that the server decides how fast the remote client can push the data of the request body.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Connecting to this service with a slow HTTP client would backpressure so that the next random number is produced on demand with constant memory usage on the server.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Akka HTTP routes easily interact with actors.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] In this example one route allows for placing bids in a fire-and-forget style while the second route contains a request-response interaction with an actor.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] The resulting response is rendered as JSON and returned when the response arrives from the actor.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] More details on how JSON marshalling and unmarshalling works can be found in the JSON Support section.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Read more about the details of the high level APIs in the section High-level Server-Side API.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] The low-level Akka HTTP server APIs allows for handling connections or individual requests by accepting `HttpRequest``HttpRequest` s and answering them by producing `HttpResponse``HttpResponse` s.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] This is provided by the `akka-http-core` module, which is included automatically when you depend on `akka-http` but can also be used on its own.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] APIs for handling such request-responses as function calls and as a `Flow<HttpRequest, HttpResponse, ?>``Flow[HttpRequest, HttpResponse, _]` are available.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Read more details about the low level APIs in the section Core Server API.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Read more about the details of the client APIs in the section Consuming HTTP-based Services (Client-Side).
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Higher-level functionality, like (un)marshalling, (de)compression as well as a powerful DSL for defining HTTP-based APIs on the server-side, this is the recommended way to write HTTP servers with Akka HTTP.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] A complete, mostly low-level, server- and client-side implementation of HTTP (incl.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Provides directives for validating and extracting JSON Web Tokens (JWT) from requests.
[src:akka-http-scala/introduction] Please feel free to edit and contribute a pull request.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] The APIs of NIO were designed to provide access to the low-level I/O operations of modern operating systems.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] Although the APIs are themselves relatively high-level, the intent is to facilitate an implementation that can directly use the most efficient operations of the underlying platform.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] The Java NIO APIs are provided in the `java.nio` package and its subpackages.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] The documentation by Oracle identifies these features.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] NIO data transfer is based on buffers (`java.nio.Buffer` and related classes).
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] These classes represent a contiguous extent of memory, together with a small number of data transfer operations.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] Although theoretically these are general-purpose data structures, the implementation may select memory for alignment or paging characteristics, which are not otherwise accessible in Java.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] Typically, this would be used to allow the buffer contents to occupy the same physical memory used by the underlying operating system for its native I/O operations, thus allowing the most direct transfer mechanism, and eliminating the need for any additional copying.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] In most operating systems, provided the particular area of memory has the right properties, transfer can take place without using the CPU at all.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] The NIO buffer is intentionally limited in features in order to support these goals.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] There are buffer classes for all of Java's primitive types except `boolean`, which can share memory with byte buffers and allow arbitrary interpretation of the underlying bytes.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] NIO buffers maintain several pointers that dictate the function of their accessor methods.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] Channels (classes implementing the interface `java.nio.channels.Channel`) are designed to provide for bulk data transfers to and from NIO buffers.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] This is a low-level data transfer mechanism that exists in parallel with the classes of the higher-level I/O library (packages `java.io` and `java.net`).
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] A channel implementation can be obtained from a high-level data transfer class such as `java.io.File`, `java.net.ServerSocket`, or `java.net.Socket`, and vice versa.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] Channels are analogous to "file descriptors" found in Unix-like operating systems.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] File channels (`java.nio.channels.FileChannel`) can use arbitrary buffers but can also establish a buffer directly mapped to file contents using memory-mapped file.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] They can also interact with file system locks.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] Similarly, socket channels (`java.nio.channels.SocketChannel` and `java.nio.channels.ServerSocketChannel`) allow for data transfer between sockets and NIO buffers.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] `FileChannel` can be used to do a file copy, which is potentially far more efficient than using old read/write with a byte array.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] A selector (`java.nio.channels.Selector` and subclasses) provides a mechanism for waiting on channels and recognizing when one or more become available for data transfer.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] When a number of channels are registered with the selector, it enables blocking of the program flow until at least one channel is ready for use, or until an interruption condition occurs.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] Although this multiplexing behavior could be implemented with threads, the selector can provide a significantly more efficient implementation using lower-level operating system constructs.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] A POSIX-compliant operating system, for example, would have direct representations of these concepts, select().
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] A notable application of this design would be the common paradigm in server software which involves simultaneously waiting for responses on a number of sessions.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] In Java, a character set is a mapping between Unicode characters (or a subset of them) and bytes.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] The `java.nio.charset` package of NIO provides facilities for identifying character sets and providing encoding and decoding algorithms for new mappings.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] It is unexpected that a `java.nio.channels.Channel` associated with a `java.io.RandomAccessFile` closes the file descriptor on an interrupt, whereas `java.io.RandomAccessFile`s' associated `java.nio.channels.FileChannel` does do this.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] JDK 7 includes a `java.nio.file` package which, with the `Path` class (also new to JDK 7), among other features, provides extended capabilities for filesystem tasks, e.g. can work with symbolic/hard links and dump big directory listings into buffers more quickly than the old File class does.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] The `java.nio.file` package and its related package, `java.nio.file.attribute`, provide comprehensive support for file I/O and for accessing the file system.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] A zip file system provider is also available in JDK 7.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] The `java.nio.file.LinkOption` is an example of emulating extensible enums with interfaces.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] In Java, it is not possible to have one `java.lang.Enum` extend another `Enum`.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] However, it is possible to emulate an extensible `Enum` type by having an `Enum` implement one or more interfaces.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] `LinkOption` is an enum type that implements both the `java.nio.file.OpenOption` and `java.nio.file.CopyOption` interfaces, which emulates the effects of an extensible `Enum` type.
[src:akka-http-scala/non-blocking-i-o-java] A small down-side to this approach is that implementations cannot be inherited between various `Enum` types.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] Reactive Streams started as an initiative in late 2013 between engineers at Netflix, Pivotal and Lightbend.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] Some of the earliest discussions began in 2013 between the Play and Akka teams at Lightbend.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] Lightbend is one of the main contributors of Reactive Streams.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] Other contributors include Red Hat, Oracle, Twitter and spray.io.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] The main goal of Reactive Streams is to govern the exchange of stream data across an asynchronous boundary – like passing elements on to another thread or thread-pool – while ensuring that the receiving side is not forced to buffer arbitrary amounts of data.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] In other words, back pressure is an integral part of this model in order to allow the queues which mediate between threads to be bounded.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] The intention of the specification is to allow the creation of many conforming implementations, which by virtue of abiding by the rules will be able to interoperate smoothly, preserving the mentioned benefits and characteristics across the whole processing graph of a stream application.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] A freely-available Technology Compatibility Kit was developed alongside the specification that allows implementors of the specification to verify if they covered all rules and requirements, including checks for potential race conditions.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] The scope of Reactive Streams is a minimal set of interfaces, methods and protocols that describe the necessary operations and entities to achieve the asynchronous streams of data with non-blocking back pressure.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] End-user DSLs or protocol binding APIs have purposefully been left out of the scope to encourage and enable different implementations that potentially use different programming languages to stay as true as possible to the idioms of their platform.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] The specification developed with the intent of future inclusion in the official Java standard library, if proven successful and adopted by enough libraries and vendors.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] Reactive Streams were proposed to become part of Java 9 by Doug Lea, leader of JSR 166 as a new Flow class that would include the interfaces currently provided by Reactive Streams.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] After a successful 1.0 release of Reactive Streams and growing adoption, the proposal was accepted and Reactive Streams was included in JDK9 via the JEP-266.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] On April 30, 2015 version 1.0.0 of Reactive Streams for the JVM was released, including Java API, a textual specification, a TCK and implementation examples.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] Other implementations include Cassandra, Elasticsearch, Apache Kafka, Parallel Universe Quasar, Play Framework, Armeria.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] Spring 5 is announced to be built upon Reactive Streams compatible Reactor Core.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] Amazon announced that its Amazon Web Services SDK would support Reactive Streams to provide streaming capabilities in its client libraries in version 2.0.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] Reactive Streams 1.0.1 is released on August 9, 2017, including various improvements in specification preciseness, TCK improvements and other clarifications.
[src:akka-http-scala/reactive-streams] The specification as well as interfaces remained fully backwards compatible with the 1.0.0 version, however aimed to streamline the adoption for future implementors as well as align with some additional requirements set by the OpenJDK.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala source code can be compiled to JVM bytecode and run on a Java virtual machine (JVM).
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala can also be transpiled to JavaScript to run in a browser, or compiled directly to a native executable using Clang.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] When running on the JVM, Scala provides language interoperability with Java so that libraries written in either language may be referenced directly in Scala or Java code.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Like Java, Scala is object-oriented, and uses a syntax termed *curly-brace* which is similar to the language C.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Since Scala 3, there is also an option to use the off-side rule (indenting) to structure blocks, and its use is advised.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Martin Odersky has said that this turned out to be the most productive change introduced in Scala 3.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Unlike Java, Scala has many features of functional programming languages (like Scheme, Standard ML, and Haskell), including currying, immutability, lazy evaluation, and pattern matching.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The name Scala is a portmanteau of *scalable* and *language*, signifying that it is designed to grow with the demands of its users.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The design of Scala started in 2001 at the École Polytechnique Fédérale de Lausanne (EPFL) (in Lausanne, Switzerland) by Martin Odersky.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] It followed on from work on Funnel, a programming language combining ideas from functional programming and Petri nets.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Odersky formerly worked on Generic Java, and javac, Sun's Java compiler.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] After an internal release in late 2003, Scala was released publicly in early 2004 on the Java platform, A second version (v2.0) followed in March 2006.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] On 17 January 2011, the Scala team won a five-year research grant of over €2.3 million from the European Research Council.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] On 12 May 2011, Odersky and collaborators launched Typesafe Inc.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] (later renamed Lightbend Inc.), a company to provide commercial support, training, and services for Scala.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Typesafe received a $3 million investment in 2011 from Greylock Partners.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala runs on the Java platform (Java virtual machine) and is compatible with existing Java programs.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The reference Scala software distribution, including compiler and libraries, is released under the Apache license.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala Native is a Scala compiler that targets the LLVM compiler infrastructure to create executable code that uses a lightweight managed runtime, which uses the Boehm garbage collector.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The project is led by Denys Shabalin and had its first release, 0.1, on 14 March 2017.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Development of Scala Native began in 2015 with a goal of being faster than just-in-time compilation for the JVM by eliminating the initial runtime compilation of code and also providing the ability to call native routines directly.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] A reference Scala compiler targeting the .NET Framework and its Common Language Runtime was released in June 2004, but was officially dropped in 2012.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Unlike the stand-alone Hello World application for Java, there is no class declaration and nothing is declared to be static.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] This is analogous to the process for compiling and running Java code.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Indeed, Scala's compiling and executing model is identical to that of Java, making it compatible with Java build tools such as Apache Ant.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala includes an interactive shell and scripting support.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example shows the differences between Java and Scala syntax.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] These syntactic relaxations are designed to allow support for domain-specific languages.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example contrasts the definition of classes in Java and Scala.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala has the same compiling model as Java and C#, namely separate compiling and dynamic class loading, so that Scala code can call Java libraries.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala's operational characteristics are the same as Java's.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The Scala compiler generates byte code that is nearly identical to that generated by the Java compiler.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] In fact, Scala code can be decompiled to readable Java code, with the exception of certain constructor operations.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] To the Java virtual machine (JVM), Scala code and Java code are indistinguishable.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The only difference is one extra runtime library, `scala-library.jar`.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala adds a large number of features compared with Java, and has some fundamental differences in its underlying model of expressions and types, which make the language theoretically cleaner and eliminate several *corner cases* in Java.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] From the Scala perspective, this is practically important because several added features in Scala are also available in C#.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] As mentioned above, Scala has a good deal of syntactic flexibility, compared with Java.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] By themselves, these may seem like questionable choices, but collectively they serve the purpose of allowing domain-specific languages to be defined in Scala without needing to extend the compiler.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] For example, Erlang's special syntax for sending a message to an actor, i.e.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] `actor ! message` can be (and is) implemented in a Scala library without needing language extensions.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Java makes a sharp distinction between primitive types (e.g.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] `int` and `boolean`) and reference types (any class).
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Only reference types are part of the inheritance scheme, deriving from `java.lang.Object`.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] In Scala, all types inherit from a top-level class `Any`, whose immediate children are `AnyVal` (value types, such as `Int` and `Boolean`) and `AnyRef` (reference types, as in Java).
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] This means that the Java distinction between primitive types and boxed types (e.g.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] `Integer`) is not present in Scala; boxing and unboxing is completely transparent to the user.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala 2.10 allows for new value types to be defined by the user.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Instead of the Java "foreach" loops for looping through an iterator, Scala has `for`-expressions, which are similar to list comprehensions in languages such as Haskell, or a combination of list comprehensions and generator expressions in Python.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] For-expressions using the `yield` keyword allow a new collection to be generated by iterating over an existing one, returning a new collection of the same type.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] They are translated by the compiler into a series of `map`, `flatMap` and `filter` calls.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Where `yield` is not used, the code approximates to an imperative-style loop, by translating to `foreach`.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] (The expression `1 to 25` is not special syntax.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Expression `(mention, times) <- mentions` is an example of pattern matching (see below).
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Iterating over a map returns a set of key-value tuples, and pattern-matching allows the tuples to easily be destructured into separate variables for the key and value.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Similarly, the result of the comprehension also returns key-value tuples, which are automatically built back up into a map because the source object (from the variable `mentions`) is a map.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] If `mentions` instead held a list, set, array or other collection of tuples, exactly the same code above would yield a new collection of the same type.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] While supporting all of the object-oriented features available in Java (and in fact, augmenting them in various ways), Scala also provides a large number of capabilities that are normally found only in functional programming languages.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Together, these features allow Scala programs to be written in an almost completely functional style and also allow functional and object-oriented styles to be mixed.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Unlike C or Java, but similar to languages such as Lisp, Scala makes no distinction between statements and expressions.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] All statements are in fact expressions that evaluate to some value.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Functions that would be declared as returning `void` in C or Java, and statements like `while` that logically do not return a value, are in Scala considered to return the type `Unit`, which is a singleton type, with only one object of that type.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Functions and operators that never return at all (e.g. the `throw` operator or a function that always exits non-locally using an exception) logically have return type `Nothing`, a special type containing no objects; that is, a bottom type, i.e. a subclass of every possible type.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Similarly, an `if-then-else` "statement" is actually an expression, which produces a value, i.e. the result of evaluating one of the two branches.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] For similar reasons, `return` statements are unnecessary in Scala, and in fact are discouraged.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] As in Lisp, the last expression in a block of code is the value of that block of code, and if the block of code is the body of a function, it will be returned by the function.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Due to type inference, the type of variables, function return values, and many other expressions can typically be omitted, as the compiler can deduce it.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Examples are `val x = "foo"` (for an immutable constant or immutable object) or `var x = 1.5` (for a variable whose value can later be changed).
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Type inference in Scala is essentially local, in contrast to the more global Hindley-Milner algorithm used in Haskell, ML and other more purely functional languages.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] This is done to facilitate object-oriented programming.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The result is that certain types still need to be declared (most notably, function parameters, and the return types of recursive functions), e.g.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] In Scala, functions are objects, and a convenient syntax exists for specifying anonymous functions.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] An example is the expression `x => x < 2`, which specifies a function with one parameter, that compares its argument to see if it is less than 2.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] It is equivalent to the Lisp form `(lambda (x) (< x 2))`.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Neither the type of x nor the return type need be explicitly specified, and can generally be inferred by type inference; but they can be explicitly specified, e.g., as `(x: Int) => x < 2` or even `(x: Int) => (x < 2): Boolean`.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Anonymous functions behave as true closures in that they automatically capture any variables that are lexically available in the environment of the enclosing function.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Those variables will be available even after the enclosing function returns, and unlike in the case of Java's *anonymous inner classes* do not need to be declared as final.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala enforces a distinction between immutable and mutable variables.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Mutable variables are declared using the `var` keyword and immutable values are declared using the `val` keyword.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] A variable declared using the `val` keyword cannot be reassigned in the same way that a variable declared using the `final` keyword can't be reassigned in Java.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] `val`s are only shallowly immutable, that is, an object referenced by a val is not guaranteed to itself be immutable.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Immutable classes are encouraged by convention however, and the Scala standard library provides a rich set of immutable collection classes.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala provides mutable and immutable variants of most collection classes, and the immutable version is always used unless the mutable version is explicitly imported.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The immutable variants are persistent data structures that always return an updated copy of an old object instead of updating the old object destructively in place.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] An example of this is immutable linked lists where prepending an element to a list is done by returning a new list node consisting of the element and a reference to the list tail.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Appending an element to a list can only be done by prepending all elements in the old list to a new list with only the new element.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] In the same way, inserting an element in the middle of a list will copy the first half of the list, but keep a reference to the second half of the list.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] This allows for very easy concurrency — no locks are needed as no shared objects are ever modified.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Evaluation is strict ("eager") by default.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] In other words, Scala evaluates expressions as soon as they are available, rather than as needed.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] However, it is possible to declare a variable non-strict ("lazy") with the `lazy` keyword, meaning that the code to produce the variable's value will not be evaluated until the first time the variable is referenced.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Non-strict collections of various types also exist (such as the type `Stream`, a non-strict linked list), and any collection can be made non-strict with the `view` method.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Non-strict collections provide a good semantic fit to things like server-produced data, where the evaluation of the code to generate later elements of a list (that in turn triggers a request to a server, possibly located somewhere else on the web) only happens when the elements are actually needed.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Functional programming languages commonly provide tail call optimization to allow for extensive use of recursion without stack overflow problems.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Limitations in JVM bytecode complicate tail call optimization on the JVM.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] In general, a function that calls itself with a tail call can be optimized, but mutually recursive functions cannot.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Trampolines have been suggested as a workaround.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Trampoline support has been provided by the Scala library with the object `scala.util.control.TailCalls` since Scala 2.8.0 (released 14 July 2010).
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] A function may optionally be annotated with `@tailrec`, in which case it will not compile unless it is tail recursive.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] An example of this optimization could be implemented using the factorial definition.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] This ensures tail call optimization and thus prevents a stack overflow error.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala has built-in support for pattern matching, which can be thought of as a more sophisticated, extensible version of a switch statement, where arbitrary data types can be matched (rather than just simple types like integers, Booleans and strings), including arbitrary nesting.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] A special type of class known as a *case class* is provided, which includes automatic support for pattern matching and can be used to model the algebraic data types used in many functional programming languages.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The idea here is that we partition a list into the elements less than a pivot and the elements not less, recursively sort each part, and paste the results together with the pivot in between.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] This uses the same divide-and-conquer strategy of mergesort and other fast sorting algorithms.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The `match` operator is used to do pattern matching on the object stored in `list`.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Each `case` expression is tried in turn to see if it will match, and the first match determines the result.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] In this case, `Nil` only matches the literal object `Nil`, but `pivot :: tail` matches a non-empty list, and simultaneously *destructures* the list according to the pattern given.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] In this case, the associated code will have access to a local variable named `pivot` holding the head of the list, and another variable `tail` holding the tail of the list.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] These variables are read-only, and are semantically very similar to variable bindings established using the `let` operator in Lisp and Scheme.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Pattern matching also happens in local variable declarations.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] In this case, the return value of the call to `tail.partition` is a tuple — in this case, two lists.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] (Tuples differ from other types of containers, e.g. lists, in that they are always of fixed size and the elements can be of differing types — although here they are both the same.) Pattern matching is the easiest way of fetching the two parts of the tuple.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The form `_ < pivot` is a declaration of an anonymous function with a placeholder variable; see the section above on anonymous functions.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The list operators `::` (which adds an element onto the beginning of a list, similar to `cons` in Lisp and Scheme) and `:::` (which appends two lists together, similar to `append` in Lisp and Scheme) both appear.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Despite appearances, there is nothing "built-in" about either of these operators.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] As specified above, any string of symbols can serve as function name, and a method applied to an object can be written "infix"-style without the period or parentheses.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] In the pattern-matching example above, the body of the `match` operator is a partial function, which consists of a series of `case` expressions, with the first matching expression prevailing, similar to the body of a switch statement.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Finally, a partial function can be used alone, and the result of calling it is equivalent to doing a `match` over it.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Here a read-only *variable* is declared whose type is a function from lists of integers to lists of integers, and bind it to a partial function.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala is a pure object-oriented language in the sense that every value is an object.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Data types and behaviors of objects are described by classes and traits.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Class abstractions are extended by subclassing and by a flexible mixin-based composition mechanism to avoid the problems of multiple inheritance.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Traits are Scala's replacement for Java's interfaces.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Interfaces in Java versions under 8 are highly restricted, able only to contain abstract function declarations.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] This has led to criticism that providing convenience methods in interfaces is awkward (the same methods must be reimplemented in every implementation), and extending a published interface in a backwards-compatible way is impossible.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Traits are similar to mixin classes in that they have nearly all the power of a regular abstract class, lacking only class parameters (Scala's equivalent to Java's constructor parameters), since traits are always mixed in with a class.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The `super` operator behaves specially in traits, allowing traits to be chained using composition in addition to inheritance.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] In other words, the call to `draw` first executed the code in `TitleDecoration` (the last trait mixed in), then (through the `super()` calls) threaded back through the other mixed-in traits and eventually to the code in `Window`, *even though none of the traits inherited from one another*.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] This is similar to the decorator pattern, but is more concise and less error-prone, as it doesn't require explicitly encapsulating the parent window, explicitly forwarding functions whose implementation isn't changed, or relying on run-time initialization of entity relationships.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] In other languages, a similar effect could be achieved at compile-time with a long linear chain of implementation inheritance, but with the disadvantage compared to Scala that one linear inheritance chain would have to be declared for each possible combination of the mix-ins.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala is equipped with an expressive static type system that mostly enforces the safe and coherent use of abstractions.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] This makes most static type declarations optional.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Static types need not be explicitly declared unless a compiler error indicates the need.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] In practice, some static type declarations are included for the sake of code clarity.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] A common technique in Scala, known as "enrich my library" (originally termed "pimp my library" by Martin Odersky in 2006; concerns were raised about this phrasing due to its negative connotations and immaturity), allows new methods to be used as if they were added to existing types.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] This is similar to the C# concept of extension methods but more powerful, because the technique is not limited to adding methods and can, for instance, be used to implement new interfaces.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] In Scala, this technique involves declaring an implicit conversion from the type "receiving" the method to a new type (typically, a class) that wraps the original type and provides the additional method.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] If a method cannot be found for a given type, the compiler automatically searches for any applicable implicit conversions to types that provide the method in question.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] This technique allows new methods to be added to an existing class using an add-on library such that only code that *imports* the add-on library gets the new functionality, and all other code is unaffected.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Importing the members of `MyExtensions` brings the implicit conversion to extension class `IntPredicates` into scope.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala's standard library includes support for futures and promises, in addition to the standard Java concurrency APIs.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Originally, it also included support for the actor model, which is now available as a separate source-available platform Akka licensed by Lightbend Inc.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Akka actors may be distributed or combined with software transactional memory (*transactors*).
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Alternative communicating sequential processes (CSP) implementations for channel-based message passing are Communicating Scala Objects, or simply via JCSP.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] An Actor is like a thread instance with a mailbox.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] It can be created by `system.actorOf`, overriding the `receive` method to receive messages and using the `!` (exclamation point) method to send a message.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example shows an EchoServer that can receive messages and then print them.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Scala also comes with built-in support for data-parallel programming in the form of Parallel Collections integrated into its Standard Library since version 2.9.0.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The following example shows how to use Parallel Collections to improve performance.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Besides futures and promises, actor support, and data parallelism, Scala also supports asynchronous programming with software transactional memory, and event streams.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] The most well-known open-source cluster-computing solution written in Scala is Apache Spark.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] Additionally, Apache Kafka, the publish–subscribe message queue popular with Spark and other stream processing technologies, is written in Scala.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] There are several ways to test code in Scala.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] ScalaTest supports multiple testing styles and can integrate with Java-based testing frameworks.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] ScalaCheck is a library similar to Haskell's QuickCheck. specs2 is a library for writing executable software specifications.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] ScalaMock provides support for testing high-order and curried functions.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p01] JUnit and TestNG are popular testing frameworks written in Java.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] Scala is often compared with Groovy and Clojure, two other programming languages also using the JVM.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] Substantial differences between these languages exist in the type system, in the extent to which each language supports object-oriented and functional programming, and in the similarity of their syntax to that of Java.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] Scala is statically typed, while both Groovy and Clojure are dynamically typed.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] This makes the type system more complex and difficult to understand but allows almost all type errors to be caught at compile-time and can result in significantly faster execution.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] By contrast, dynamic typing requires more testing to ensure program correctness, and thus is generally slower, to allow greater programming flexibility and simplicity.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] Regarding speed differences, current versions of Groovy and Clojure allow optional type annotations to help programs avoid the overhead of dynamic typing in cases where types are practically static.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] This overhead is further reduced when using recent versions of the JVM, which has been enhanced with an *invoke dynamic* instruction for methods that are defined with dynamically typed arguments.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] These advances reduce the speed gap between static and dynamic typing, although a statically typed language, like Scala, is still the preferred choice when execution efficiency is very important.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] Regarding programming paradigms, Scala inherits the object-oriented model of Java and extends it in various ways.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] Groovy, while also strongly object-oriented, is more focused in reducing verbosity.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] In Clojure, object-oriented programming is deemphasised with functional programming being the main strength of the language.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] Scala also has many functional programming facilities, including features found in advanced functional languages like Haskell, and tries to be agnostic between the two paradigms, letting the developer choose between the two paradigms or, more frequently, some combination thereof.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] Regarding syntax similarity with Java, Scala inherits much of Java's syntax, as is the case with Groovy.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] Clojure on the other hand follows the Lisp syntax, which is different in both appearance and philosophy.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] Back in 2013, when Scala was in version 2.10, the ThoughtWorks Technology Radar, which is an opinion based biannual report of a group of senior technologists, recommended Scala adoption in its languages and frameworks category.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] In the 2018 edition of the *State of Java* survey, which collected data from 5160 developers on various Java-related topics, Scala places third in terms of use of alternative languages on the JVM.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] Relative to the prior year's edition of the survey, Scala's use among alternative JVM languages fell from 28.4% to 21.5%, overtaken by Kotlin, which rose from 11.4% in 2017 to 28.8% in 2018.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] The Popularity of Programming Language Index, which tracks searches for language tutorials, ranked Scala 15th in April 2018 with a small downward trend, and 17th in Jan 2021.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] This makes Scala the 3rd most popular JVM-based language after Java and Kotlin, ranked 12th.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] The RedMonk Programming Language Rankings, which establishes rankings based on the number of GitHub projects and questions asked on Stack Overflow, in January 2021 ranked Scala 14th.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] Here, Scala was placed inside a second-tier group of languages–ahead of Go, PowerShell, and Haskell, and behind Swift, Objective-C, TypeScript, and R.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] The TIOBE index of programming language popularity employs internet search engine rankings and similar publication counting to determine language popularity.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] In September 2021, it showed Scala in 31st place.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] In this ranking, Scala was ahead of Haskell (38th) and Erlang, but below Go (14th), Swift (15th), and Perl (19th).
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] As of 2022, JVM-based languages such as Clojure, Groovy, and Scala are highly ranked, but still significantly less popular than the original Java language, which is usually ranked in the top three places.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] In November 2011, Yammer moved away from Scala for reasons that included the learning curve for new team members and incompatibility from one version of the Scala compiler to the next.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] In March 2015, former VP of the Platform Engineering group at Twitter Raffi Krikorian, stated that he would not have chosen Scala in 2011 due to its learning curve.
[src:akka-http-scala/scala-programming-language-p02] The same month, LinkedIn SVP Kevin Scott stated their decision to "minimize [their] dependence on Scala".
